[{"id":"VR786365","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two spheres with the same radius. The top half of each sphere has net charge positive Q, and the bottom half of each sphere has net charge negative Q. The charges in the top and bottom halves of Sphere 1 are uniformly distributed over the top and bottom halves of Sphere 1, respectively. The charges in the top and bottom halves of Sphere 2 are uniformly distributed over the surfaces of the top and bottom halves of Sphere 2, respectively. Near the middle of the top half of each sphere, there is an electric field vector E pointing down. A note states that the two spheres are far apart from each other.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR786365.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two solid spheres, Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> and Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, both have the same radius, as shown in the figure. The spheres are far apart from each other and both are in electrostatic equilibrium. In Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span>, there is a net charge everywhere within the sphere’s volume: a charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive Q\"><math alttext=\"positive Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></math></span></span> uniformly distributed throughout the top half of the sphere, and a charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative Q\"><math alttext=\"negative Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>-</mo><mi>Q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span> uniformly distributed throughout the bottom half of the sphere. In Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span>, there is a net charge over the entire surface but not inside the sphere: a charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive Q\"><math alttext=\"positive Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>Q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span> uniformly distributed over the top half of the sphere’s surface, and a charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"negative Q\"><math alttext=\"negative Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>-</mo><mi>Q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span> uniformly distributed over the bottom half of the sphere’s surface. As indicated in the figure, there is a downward electric field in each sphere at a point located in the top half of the sphere. Which of the following correctly describes whether each sphere is a conductor or an insulator?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR786365_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> is a conductor and Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> is an insulator.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> is an insulator and Sphere <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>2</mn></math></span></span> is a conductor.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Both spheres are conductors.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Both spheres are insulators.</p>"],"answer":3}]